20#ifndef GCC_C_FORMAT_H
21#define GCC_C_FORMAT_H
22
23/* The meaningfully distinct length modifiers for format checking recognized
24 by GCC. */
25enum format_lengths
26{
27 FMT_LEN_none,
28 FMT_LEN_hh,
29 FMT_LEN_h,
30 FMT_LEN_l,
31 FMT_LEN_ll,
32 FMT_LEN_L,
33 FMT_LEN_z,
34 FMT_LEN_t,
35 FMT_LEN_j,
36 FMT_LEN_H,
37 FMT_LEN_D,
38 FMT_LEN_DD,
39 FMT_LEN_MAX
40};
41
42
43/* The standard versions in which various format features appeared. */
44enum format_std_version
45{
46 STD_C89,
47 STD_C94,
48 STD_C9L, /* C99, but treat as C89 if -Wno-long-long. */
49 STD_C99,
50 STD_EXT
51};
52
53/* Flags that may apply to a particular kind of format checked by GCC. */
54enum
55{
56 /* This format converts arguments of types determined by the
57 format string. */
58 FMT_FLAG_ARG_CONVERT = 1,
59 /* The scanf allocation 'a' kludge applies to this format kind. */
60 FMT_FLAG_SCANF_A_KLUDGE = 2,
61 /* A % during parsing a specifier is allowed to be a modified % rather
62 that indicating the format is broken and we are out-of-sync. */
63 FMT_FLAG_FANCY_PERCENT_OK = 4,
64 /* With $ operand numbers, it is OK to reference the same argument more
65 than once. */
66 FMT_FLAG_DOLLAR_MULTIPLE = 8,
67 /* This format type uses $ operand numbers (strfmon doesn't). */
68 FMT_FLAG_USE_DOLLAR = 16,
69 /* Zero width is bad in this type of format (scanf). */
70 FMT_FLAG_ZERO_WIDTH_BAD = 32,
71 /* Empty precision specification is OK in this type of format (printf). */
72 FMT_FLAG_EMPTY_PREC_OK = 64,
73 /* Gaps are allowed in the arguments with $ operand numbers if all
74 arguments are pointers (scanf). */
75 FMT_FLAG_DOLLAR_GAP_POINTER_OK = 128,
76 /* The format arg is an opaque object that will be parsed by an external
77 facility. */
78 FMT_FLAG_PARSE_ARG_CONVERT_EXTERNAL = 256,
79 /* Not included here: details of whether width or precision may occur
80 (controlled by width_char and precision_char); details of whether
81 '*' can be used for these (width_type and precision_type); details
82 of whether length modifiers can occur (length_char_specs). */
83 FMT_FLAG_M_OK = 512
84 /* %m is only allowed in syslog */
85};
86
87/* Structure describing a length modifier supported in format checking, and
88 possibly a doubled version such as "hh". */
89struct format_length_info
90{
91 /* Name of the single-character length modifier. If prefixed by
92 a zero character, it describes a multi character length
93 modifier, like I64, I32, etc. */
94 const char *name;
95 /* Index into a format_char_info.types array. */
96 enum format_lengths index;
97 /* Standard version this length appears in. */
98 enum format_std_version std;
99 /* Same, if the modifier can be repeated, or NULL if it can't. */
100 const char *double_name;
101 enum format_lengths double_index;
102 enum format_std_version double_std;
103
104 /* If this flag is set, just scalar width identity is checked, and
105 not the type identity itself. */
106 int scalar_identity_flag;
107};
108
109
110/* Structure describing the combination of a conversion specifier
111 (or a set of specifiers which act identically) and a length modifier. */
112struct format_type_detail
113{
114 /* The standard version this combination of length and type appeared in.
115 This is only relevant if greater than those for length and type
116 individually; otherwise it is ignored. */
117 enum format_std_version std;
118 /* The name to use for the type, if different from that generated internally
119 (e.g., "signed size_t"). */
120 const char *name;
121 /* The type itself. */
122 tree *type;
123};
124

126/* Macros to fill out tables of these. */
127#define NOARGUMENTS { T89_V, BADLEN, BADLEN, BADLEN, BADLEN, BADLEN, BADLEN, BADLEN, BADLEN }
128#define BADLEN { STD_C89, NULL, NULL }
129#define NOLENGTHS { BADLEN, BADLEN, BADLEN, BADLEN, BADLEN, BADLEN, BADLEN, BADLEN, BADLEN }

131
132/* Structure describing a format conversion specifier (or a set of specifiers
133 which act identically), and the length modifiers used with it. */
134struct format_char_info
135{
136 const char *format_chars;
137 int pointer_count;
138 enum format_std_version std;
139 /* Types accepted for each length modifier. */
140 format_type_detail types[FMT_LEN_MAX];
141 /* List of other modifier characters allowed with these specifiers.
142 This lists flags, and additionally "w" for width, "p" for precision
143 (right precision, for strfmon), "#" for left precision (strfmon),
144 "a" for scanf "a" allocation extension (not applicable in C99 mode),
145 "*" for scanf suppression, and "E" and "O" for those strftime
146 modifiers. */
147 const char *flag_chars;
148 /* List of additional flags describing these conversion specifiers.
149 "c" for generic character pointers being allowed, "2" for strftime
150 two digit year formats, "3" for strftime formats giving two digit
151 years in some locales, "4" for "2" which becomes "3" with an "E" modifier,
152 "o" if use of strftime "O" is a GNU extension beyond C99,
153 "W" if the argument is a pointer which is dereferenced and written into,
154 "R" if the argument is a pointer which is dereferenced and read from,
155 "i" for printf integer formats where the '0' flag is ignored with
156 precision, and "[" for the starting character of a scanf scanset. */
157 const char *flags2;
158 /* If this format conversion character consumes more than one argument,
159 CHAIN points to information about the next argument. For later
160 arguments, only POINTER_COUNT, TYPES, and the "c", "R", and "W" flags
161 in FLAGS2 are used. */
162 const struct format_char_info *chain;
163};
164
165
166/* Structure describing a flag accepted by some kind of format. */
167struct format_flag_spec
168{
169 /* The flag character in question (0 for end of array). */
170 int flag_char;
171 /* Zero if this entry describes the flag character in general, or a
172 nonzero character that may be found in flags2 if it describes the
173 flag when used with certain formats only. If the latter, only
174 the first such entry found that applies to the current conversion
175 specifier is used; the values of 'name' and 'long_name' it supplies
176 will be used, if non-NULL and the standard version is higher than
177 the unpredicated one, for any pedantic warning. For example, 'o'
178 for strftime formats (meaning 'O' is an extension over C99). */
179 int predicate;
180 /* Nonzero if the next character after this flag in the format should
181 be skipped ('=' in strfmon), zero otherwise. */
182 int skip_next_char;
183 /* The name to use for this flag in diagnostic messages. For example,
184 N_("'0' flag"), N_("field width"). */
185 const char *name;
186 /* Long name for this flag in diagnostic messages; currently only used for
187 "ISO C does not support ...". For example, N_("the 'I' printf flag"). */
188 const char *long_name;
189 /* The standard version in which it appeared. */
190 enum format_std_version std;
191};
192
193
194/* Structure describing a combination of flags that is bad for some kind
195 of format. */
196struct format_flag_pair
197{
198 /* The first flag character in question (0 for end of array). */
199 int flag_char1;
200 /* The second flag character. */
201 int flag_char2;
202 /* Nonzero if the message should say that the first flag is ignored with
203 the second, zero if the combination should simply be objected to. */
204 int ignored;
205 /* Zero if this entry applies whenever this flag combination occurs,
206 a nonzero character from flags2 if it only applies in some
207 circumstances (e.g. 'i' for printf formats ignoring 0 with precision). */
208 int predicate;
209};
210
211
212/* Structure describing a particular kind of format processed by GCC. */
213struct format_kind_info
214{
215 /* The name of this kind of format, for use in diagnostics. Also
216 the name of the attribute (without preceding and following __). */
217 const char *name;
218 /* Specifications of the length modifiers accepted; possibly NULL. */
219 const format_length_info *length_char_specs;
220 /* Details of the conversion specification characters accepted. */
221 const format_char_info *conversion_specs;
222 /* String listing the flag characters that are accepted. */
223 const char *flag_chars;
224 /* String listing modifier characters (strftime) accepted. May be NULL. */
225 const char *modifier_chars;
226 /* Details of the flag characters, including pseudo-flags. */
227 const format_flag_spec *flag_specs;
228 /* Details of bad combinations of flags. */
229 const format_flag_pair *bad_flag_pairs;
230 /* Flags applicable to this kind of format. */
231 int flags;
232 /* Flag character to treat a width as, or 0 if width not used. */
233 int width_char;
234 /* Flag character to treat a left precision (strfmon) as,
235 or 0 if left precision not used. */
236 int left_precision_char;
237 /* Flag character to treat a precision (for strfmon, right precision) as,
238 or 0 if precision not used. */
239 int precision_char;
240 /* If a flag character has the effect of suppressing the conversion of
241 an argument ('*' in scanf), that flag character, otherwise 0. */
242 int suppression_char;
243 /* Flag character to treat a length modifier as (ignored if length
244 modifiers not used). Need not be placed in flag_chars for conversion
245 specifiers, but is used to check for bad combinations such as length
246 modifier with assignment suppression in scanf. */
247 int length_code_char;
248 /* Assignment-allocation flag character ('m' in scanf), otherwise 0. */
249 int alloc_char;
250 /* Pointer to type of argument expected if '*' is used for a width,
251 or NULL if '*' not used for widths. */
252 tree *width_type;
253 /* Pointer to type of argument expected if '*' is used for a precision,
254 or NULL if '*' not used for precisions. */
255 tree *precision_type;
256 /* A format type that is a subset of our format */
257 int parent_format_type;
258};

320/* Structure describing how format attributes such as "printf" are
321 interpreted as "gnu_printf" or "ms_printf" on a particular system.
322 TARGET_OVERRIDES_FORMAT_ATTRIBUTES is used to specify target-specific
323 defaults. */
324struct target_ovr_attr
325{
326 /* The name of the to be copied format attribute. */
327 const char *named_attr_src;
328 /* The name of the to be overridden format attribute. */
329 const char *named_attr_dst;
330};
